Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Once water is boiling, add @penne pasta{6%ounce} and cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{12%minutes}. Scoop out and reserve ½ cup pasta cooking water, then drain.

Meanwhile, wash and dry all produce. Drain @capers{1%ounce}; thoroughly pat dry with #paper towels{}. Trim off and discard woody ends from @asparagus{8%ounce}; cut crosswise into 1-inch pieces. Dice @Roma tomato{1}. Zest 1 tsp zest from @lemon{1}; quarter lemon.

Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%tablespoon} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Once oil is hot enough that a caper sizzles immediately when added to the pan, add capers and cook, stirring occasionally, until crispy, ~{2%minutes}. Carefully transfer capers to a paper-towel-lined #plate{}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add asparagus and a pinch of @chili flakes{1%teaspoon}. Cook, stirring often, until bright green, ~{4%minutes}. Add tomato and cook, stirring, until slightly softened, ~{2%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Add penne, @garlic herb butter{2%tablespoon}, half the @Parmesan cheese{1/4%cup}, and ⅓ cup reserved pasta cooking water to pan. Season with salt and pepper. Stir until thoroughly combined and a loose sauce has formed. (TIP: If sauce seems dry, stir in remaining cooking water a splash at a time.) Turn off heat; stir in a squeeze of lemon juice.

Divide pasta between bowls. Sprinkle with remaining Parmesan, a drizzle of @olive oil{1%teaspoon} and as many crispy capers as you like (you may have capers leftover). Garnish with lemon zest and additional chili flakes (to taste). Serve with remaining lemon wedges on the side for squeezing over.